body:
## Steps to reproduce the issue

original design:

```
module dut ( 
    input clk 
    ,input ce 
    ,input we 
    ,input [3:0] bwe 
    ,input [5:0] addr 
    ,input [3:0] data 
    ,output reg [3:0] q 
); 

    reg [3:0] mem [0:32] ;
    
    always @ (posedge clk) begin
        if (ce && we) begin
            mem[addr] = (data & bwe) | (mem[addr] & ~bwe); 
        end
        if (!ce) begin
            q <= mem[addr];
        end
    end

endmodule 
```

Yosys script:

```
read -sv primary.sv
hierarchy -check -top dut
opt
write_verilog -noattr out.sv
```

Output:

```
module dut(clk, ce, we, addr, data, q, bwe);
  wire [3:0] _00_;
  wire [3:0] _01_;
  wire [3:0] _02_;
  wire [3:0] _03_;
  wire _04_;
  wire [3:0] _05_;
  input [5:0] addr;
  input [3:0] bwe;
  input ce;
  input clk;
  input [3:0] data;
  output [3:0] q;
  reg [3:0] q;
  input we;
  reg [3:0] mem [63:0];
  always @(posedge clk) begin
    if (_04_)
      mem[addr] <= _03_;
  end
  assign _00_ = mem[addr];
  always @(posedge clk)
    if (!ce) q <= _00_;
  assign _05_ = data & bwe;
  assign _02_ = _00_ & _01_;
  assign _04_ = ce & we;
  assign _01_ = ~ bwe;
  assign _03_ = _05_ | _02_;
endmodule
```

## Expected behavior
the memory in output should be reg [3:0] mem **[32:0]** ;

## Actual behavior
The memory in generated output is reg [3:0] mem **[63:0]** 

This happens due to the following in Verific frontend (in verific.cc lines 1088-1090)

```
int number_of_bits = net->Size();
number_of_bits = 1 << ceil_log2(number_of_bits);
int bits_in_word = number_of_bits;
```

The net->Size() is 132 (33*4), the log2 is 8 thus the shift operation results to 2^8 = 256, then in line 1105 the memory size is calculated:

`memory->size = number_of_bits / bits_in_word;
`

so it becomes 256/4 (bits_in_word is 4) = 64, i.e. [63:0], but it should be 132/4 = 33 bits, i.e. [32:0].

I think the number_of_bits should not be updated in line 1089 and bits_in_word can be set like the following (later it is updated based on ram input/output ports size):

`bits_in_word = 1 << ceil_log2(number_of_bits);
`

Note the memory size is correct with read_verilog:

```
read_verilog  -nomem2reg primary.sv
hierarchy -check -top dut
proc
opt
write_verilog -noattr rverilog.sv
```

in the output:

`reg [3:0] mem [32:0];`

